Well, thank you.

00:00:07.556 --> 00:00:09.170
It's great to see all of you.

00:00:09.170 --> 00:00:11.490
And I want to thank
Google for the invitation.

00:00:11.490 --> 00:00:12.907
I'm a fan of the
company and have

00:00:12.907 --> 00:00:14.990
enjoyed working with all
of you through the years.

00:00:14.990 --> 00:00:17.130
So it's good to have
faces with the company.

00:00:17.130 --> 00:00:18.770
So thank you.

00:00:18.770 --> 00:00:22.610
And so in talking to a couple of
the folks prior to this event,

00:00:22.610 --> 00:00:26.240
the term intersectionality came
up, where I think all of you

00:00:26.240 --> 00:00:28.100
are focusing on the
intersection of all

00:00:28.100 --> 00:00:29.690
of our different
parts of our lives

00:00:29.690 --> 00:00:31.070
and how that comes together.

00:00:31.070 --> 00:00:32.486
So I'm probably
going to come back

00:00:32.486 --> 00:00:34.610
to that as we talk through
some of the questions

00:00:34.610 --> 00:00:36.560
and hopefully take
some of your questions.

00:00:36.560 --> 00:00:39.470
But just by way of
introduction, to think

00:00:39.470 --> 00:00:41.960
about all the
different hats I wear,

00:00:41.960 --> 00:00:44.800
yes, I'm an executive
during most days.

00:00:44.800 --> 00:00:48.590
I'm also a mom of a 15-year-old
and three-- well, two dogs

00:00:48.590 --> 00:00:51.140
and one cat, a wife.

00:00:51.140 --> 00:00:53.600
I serve on a national board.

00:00:53.600 --> 00:00:57.140
I am the chair of the board of
my daughter's private school.

00:00:57.140 --> 00:00:59.570
And I also am a
deacon at my church.

00:00:59.570 --> 00:01:01.880
So you think about
all the intersections

00:01:01.880 --> 00:01:06.500
of the LGBT family, your work
family, and then all the ways

00:01:06.500 --> 00:01:08.899
we try to give back to the
different parts of our lives

00:01:08.899 --> 00:01:09.690
that are important.

00:01:09.690 --> 00:01:11.840
So hopefully we can
touch on a number

00:01:11.840 --> 00:01:12.980
of those different areas.

00:01:12.980 --> 00:01:14.855
And I probably have
other hats that I totally

00:01:14.855 --> 00:01:16.867
forgot and whatnot.

00:01:16.867 --> 00:01:18.200
But a little bit about my story.

00:01:18.200 --> 00:01:19.380
I'm from South Louisiana.

00:01:19.380 --> 00:01:21.677
So I am one of the
real Cajuns, even

00:01:21.677 --> 00:01:24.260
though my last name doesn't show
it, my mother was a Primeaux.

00:01:24.260 --> 00:01:26.180
And if you have any
Cajun jokes, it's

00:01:26.180 --> 00:01:29.870
the Thibodeauxs,
Boudreauxs, Primeauxs, OK.

00:01:29.870 --> 00:01:32.270
So I am I'm one of
those Cajun folks.

00:01:32.270 --> 00:01:34.102
And so from a very
young age, I always

00:01:34.102 --> 00:01:35.810
knew I was different
from a lot of folks.

00:01:35.810 --> 00:01:38.210
So like many of you
probably, I took

00:01:38.210 --> 00:01:41.740
upon myself to be like
perfect at everything,

00:01:41.740 --> 00:01:45.470
be whatever, the
head of everything,

00:01:45.470 --> 00:01:47.780
so that once people figured
out that I was different,

00:01:47.780 --> 00:01:49.940
they would still kind
of maybe like me.

00:01:49.940 --> 00:01:51.240
And so I took that path.

00:01:51.240 --> 00:01:55.050
And I know a lot of people took
similar paths in their life.

00:01:55.050 --> 00:01:59.600
My coming out story is kind
of a funny one in that my--

00:01:59.600 --> 00:02:01.450
the story goes like this.

00:02:01.450 --> 00:02:05.150
I was at college and my mother
called in a panic saying,

00:02:05.150 --> 00:02:08.220
oh my god, Renee, your
sister is a lesbian.

00:02:08.220 --> 00:02:10.970
But I've always known about you,
but, really, your sister too?

00:02:10.970 --> 00:02:12.650
I was like, well,
great, thanks mom.

00:02:12.650 --> 00:02:13.858
That was always very obvious.

00:02:16.140 --> 00:02:18.450
So that's an important
part of my story.

00:02:18.450 --> 00:02:21.560
My parents went two for
two and have two gay kids.

00:02:21.560 --> 00:02:24.740
My sister runs the MCC
church for a little bit,

00:02:24.740 --> 00:02:26.396
so she's the gay pope.

00:02:26.396 --> 00:02:27.770
So you can look
up Rachelle Brown

00:02:27.770 --> 00:02:29.990
and you'll recognize the
resemblance or at least

00:02:29.990 --> 00:02:31.500
the voice.

00:02:31.500 --> 00:02:36.155
But throughout my career,
you know being a lesbian,

00:02:36.155 --> 00:02:40.610
as you know starting in banking,
it's a very conservative field.

00:02:40.610 --> 00:02:44.240
And so I wasn't out there
in my first several roles.

00:02:44.240 --> 00:02:47.150
And it really wasn't
until my partner

00:02:47.150 --> 00:02:50.690
and I decided to start a family
that the whole coming out

00:02:50.690 --> 00:02:53.489
process started in earnest,
because if you're pregnant

00:02:53.489 --> 00:02:56.030
and you're coming out, you have
to come out, because you have

00:02:56.030 --> 00:02:57.900
to explain your relationship.

00:02:57.900 --> 00:03:01.880
And so that process really
was a real turning point,

00:03:01.880 --> 00:03:04.490
not only in my personal
life in starting a family,

00:03:04.490 --> 00:03:06.380
but also in my
professional life.

00:03:06.380 --> 00:03:09.590
And a lot of people have said,
well, does having a child

00:03:09.590 --> 00:03:12.080
and coming out, does
it harm your career?

00:03:12.080 --> 00:03:14.660
In my situation, I
left on maternity leave

00:03:14.660 --> 00:03:18.947
as a person on the brand team
at Wachovia, and came back,

00:03:18.947 --> 00:03:21.530
and they immediately said you're
the head of brand management,

00:03:21.530 --> 00:03:24.200
you're a senior vice
president, it starts now.

00:03:24.200 --> 00:03:26.330
And it's like, OK, I didn't
interview for anything.

00:03:26.330 --> 00:03:28.400
I think that's against
a lot of HR policies.

00:03:28.400 --> 00:03:32.660
But you know, I started
and just jumped right in.

00:03:32.660 --> 00:03:36.969
So my experience was a very
positive one on that front.

00:03:36.969 --> 00:03:38.510
But you know, through
my career, I've

00:03:38.510 --> 00:03:42.380
been in financial services
marketing for a very long time

00:03:42.380 --> 00:03:44.509
and I've served in a
lot of different roles.

00:03:44.509 --> 00:03:46.550
I've had a chance to do
a lot of different things

00:03:46.550 --> 00:03:48.590
across financial services.

00:03:48.590 --> 00:03:50.450
And I think a part of
that is because I'm

00:03:50.450 --> 00:03:53.700
really open to taking on new
challenges and new experiences.

00:03:53.700 --> 00:03:55.700
And so as we go through
some of these questions,

00:03:55.700 --> 00:03:57.860
I hope to share some
of that, because I

00:03:57.860 --> 00:04:01.370
think the intersections
of all of our experiences

00:04:01.370 --> 00:04:04.550
make us a better worker
for whatever company

00:04:04.550 --> 00:04:06.080
we're serving at the time.

00:04:06.080 --> 00:04:09.272
So anyway, that's just a
little bit more about my story.

00:04:09.272 --> 00:04:09.980
SPEAKER 1: Great.

00:04:09.980 --> 00:04:11.445
Thank you.

00:04:11.445 --> 00:04:13.070
And could you tell
us a little bit more

00:04:13.070 --> 00:04:15.560
about the leadership
role that you're in now?

00:04:15.560 --> 00:04:17.510
What are you tasked with
and what kind of team

00:04:17.510 --> 00:04:18.135
do you oversee?

00:04:18.135 --> 00:04:20.065
And just to build
on your last point,

00:04:20.065 --> 00:04:22.190
we'd also love to hear
about some of the challenges

00:04:22.190 --> 00:04:23.770
that you're most excited
about approaching

00:04:23.770 --> 00:04:24.620
in your current role.

00:04:24.620 --> 00:04:25.620
RENEE BROWN: Absolutely.

00:04:25.620 --> 00:04:28.460
So I'm running marketing
for the retail side of TIAA.

00:04:28.460 --> 00:04:31.010
And so for folks not
familiar with TIAA,

00:04:31.010 --> 00:04:33.620
it's a 100-year-old company
that's known for retirement

00:04:33.620 --> 00:04:36.440
and helping universities
and not-for-profits

00:04:36.440 --> 00:04:38.540
in their retirement space.

00:04:38.540 --> 00:04:40.190
And we just launched
into retail.

00:04:40.190 --> 00:04:42.190
And so it's a very young
part of the company.

00:04:42.190 --> 00:04:44.180
It's really a startup
with the exception

00:04:44.180 --> 00:04:46.560
we do have an advisor
force, which is very small,

00:04:46.560 --> 00:04:48.830
about 850 advisors.

00:04:48.830 --> 00:04:51.230
The last company I left
had 15,000 advisors,

00:04:51.230 --> 00:04:54.110
so a very different scale and
scope, and a very different way

00:04:54.110 --> 00:04:55.580
of going to business.

00:04:55.580 --> 00:04:57.030
But we just purchased a bank.

00:04:57.030 --> 00:04:58.520
And so we're
integrating that bank

00:04:58.520 --> 00:05:00.650
over the next several weeks.

00:05:00.650 --> 00:05:03.836
The goal, and what my
team is responsible for,

00:05:03.836 --> 00:05:05.960
is figuring out how do we
go to market differently.

00:05:05.960 --> 00:05:07.870
We're a not-for-profit
organization.

00:05:07.870 --> 00:05:12.050
And how do we go up against
the B of A, Merrill, Chase,

00:05:12.050 --> 00:05:14.750
others in the financial
services industry like Fidelity,

00:05:14.750 --> 00:05:18.410
and show up differently and
show our not-for-profit heritage

00:05:18.410 --> 00:05:21.150
and really try to
disrupt the marketplace?

00:05:21.150 --> 00:05:24.160
And so that's the challenge
I'm taking on now.

00:05:24.160 --> 00:05:25.220
I have a small team.

00:05:25.220 --> 00:05:26.070
I haven't counted.

00:05:26.070 --> 00:05:28.580
I don't know how many people,
probably about 50 people

00:05:28.580 --> 00:05:29.600
on the team now.

00:05:29.600 --> 00:05:31.820
And it's really
exciting, because--

00:05:31.820 --> 00:05:34.890
so I was with Wachovia
Wells for 20 years.

00:05:34.890 --> 00:05:37.730
And in that whole process,
even in brand management,

00:05:37.730 --> 00:05:40.440
we were constantly trying to say
how is this company different.

00:05:40.440 --> 00:05:42.530
Well, we're on
every street corner.

00:05:42.530 --> 00:05:44.390
With the Wells example,
we have ponies.

00:05:44.390 --> 00:05:47.240
We can give out plush
ponies to people.

00:05:47.240 --> 00:05:49.620
Yes, that's a thing.

00:05:49.620 --> 00:05:52.040
But there wasn't anything
like heart and soul,

00:05:52.040 --> 00:05:53.660
whereas TIAA has a soul.

00:05:53.660 --> 00:05:56.150
And we're trying to
uncover that, and show

00:05:56.150 --> 00:05:57.942
this really cool
company, and show how

00:05:57.942 --> 00:05:59.150
it's different in the market.

00:05:59.150 --> 00:06:00.879
So it sounds like
it might be easy,

00:06:00.879 --> 00:06:02.420
but it's going to
be a challenge just

00:06:02.420 --> 00:06:04.990
with a lot of different
structures we have.

00:06:04.990 --> 00:06:06.539
So yeah, we met
with our Google team

00:06:06.539 --> 00:06:08.580
a little earlier to talk
a little bit about that.

00:06:08.580 --> 00:06:11.060
And so I'm excited
about the opportunity.

00:06:11.060 --> 00:06:12.560
SPEAKER 1: Awesome.

00:06:12.560 --> 00:06:14.150
And you touched on
this a little bit

00:06:14.150 --> 00:06:18.320
about sort of your promotion
during your maternity leave,

00:06:18.320 --> 00:06:20.750
but what path did you take
to your current role at TIAA

00:06:20.750 --> 00:06:23.700
and your path to
this previous role?

00:06:23.700 --> 00:06:26.230
RENEE BROWN: Gosh, I think--

00:06:26.230 --> 00:06:28.800
you know, some people actually
had plans for their career

00:06:28.800 --> 00:06:30.740
and I definitely didn't.

00:06:30.740 --> 00:06:34.070
The only thing consistent
with my journey

00:06:34.070 --> 00:06:37.360
is that I always took on a
job no one else wanted to do.

00:06:37.360 --> 00:06:39.200
And that has been
kind of my hallmark.

00:06:39.200 --> 00:06:41.444
And I discover that
if you raise your hand

00:06:41.444 --> 00:06:42.860
and do something
no one else wants

00:06:42.860 --> 00:06:44.870
to do that you're beloved
by the management,

00:06:44.870 --> 00:06:47.870
because it's typically something
that's hairy, complicated,

00:06:47.870 --> 00:06:50.490
political, and people
don't know the answer.

00:06:50.490 --> 00:06:52.940
And even if you can get in
and move it just a little bit,

00:06:52.940 --> 00:06:55.940
people love you and you're
kind of marked with that.

00:06:55.940 --> 00:06:59.210
So I started my career on
the regular banking side

00:06:59.210 --> 00:07:02.330
doing tons of integrations
in New Orleans for Hibernia

00:07:02.330 --> 00:07:04.190
Bank, which was
bought by Capital One,

00:07:04.190 --> 00:07:06.140
so that's how long ago that was.

00:07:06.140 --> 00:07:11.090
But it was fun being single and
26 living near Bourbon Street.

00:07:11.090 --> 00:07:13.652
And then with Wachovia, I was
on the small business side.

00:07:13.652 --> 00:07:15.110
And that was really
cool, because I

00:07:15.110 --> 00:07:16.809
got to learn how
business bankers go in

00:07:16.809 --> 00:07:17.600
and help companies.

00:07:17.600 --> 00:07:19.765
And I found that to
be very fascinating.

00:07:19.765 --> 00:07:21.515
And then when First
Union bought Wachovia,

00:07:21.515 --> 00:07:23.090
I moved into brand management.

00:07:23.090 --> 00:07:26.660
And that was a great
learning, a great ability

00:07:26.660 --> 00:07:29.330
to kind of step back and say,
how can a company be different

00:07:29.330 --> 00:07:32.014
but not just how it's expressed,
but how people actually

00:07:32.014 --> 00:07:32.930
behave at the company.

00:07:32.930 --> 00:07:34.820
And that's where
magic can happen

00:07:34.820 --> 00:07:36.620
with different institutions.

00:07:36.620 --> 00:07:39.080
But I quickly realized that
everyone's a brand expert.

00:07:39.080 --> 00:07:40.740
I don't know if
you all know that.

00:07:40.740 --> 00:07:42.660
And I got really
burned out with some

00:07:42.660 --> 00:07:43.910
of the components of branding.

00:07:43.910 --> 00:07:45.680
And so no one at
the company wanted

00:07:45.680 --> 00:07:48.620
to support the
financial advisors,

00:07:48.620 --> 00:07:51.230
because they are known
as cowboys, and cowgirls,

00:07:51.230 --> 00:07:51.897
and mean people.

00:07:51.897 --> 00:07:53.229
And I'm like, I'll take that on.

00:07:53.229 --> 00:07:54.500
So I went and got my series 7.

00:07:54.500 --> 00:07:56.749
And I'm like, OK, I'm going
to do this whole brokerage

00:07:56.749 --> 00:07:58.960
thing, and retirement
asset management.

00:07:58.960 --> 00:08:02.480
I did that for seven
years pre and post-merger

00:08:02.480 --> 00:08:03.290
with Wells Fargo.

00:08:03.290 --> 00:08:05.270
And so that was
really great learning.

00:08:05.270 --> 00:08:06.680
Did the AG Edwards integration.

00:08:06.680 --> 00:08:08.640
That was the biggest brokerage
integration in history.

00:08:08.640 --> 00:08:09.410
It was awesome.

00:08:09.410 --> 00:08:11.620
Learned so much.

00:08:11.620 --> 00:08:15.590
And then after that, I raised my
hand for another problem, which

00:08:15.590 --> 00:08:18.720
was Wells Fargo's social
media was a disaster.

00:08:18.720 --> 00:08:22.329
And so the board was kind of
standing on the management

00:08:22.329 --> 00:08:23.870
and said, you guys
have to centralize

00:08:23.870 --> 00:08:25.953
this, which the company
didn't centralize anything

00:08:25.953 --> 00:08:26.640
at the time.

00:08:26.640 --> 00:08:29.520
So I was the person who
brought social media together.

00:08:29.520 --> 00:08:30.775
And that was really fun.

00:08:30.775 --> 00:08:32.900
I kind of got out of
marketing for those few years,

00:08:32.900 --> 00:08:35.750
because, as you know,
standing up a social media

00:08:35.750 --> 00:08:37.549
platform for a
company that large,

00:08:37.549 --> 00:08:40.490
you're dealing with HR
issues, because employees

00:08:40.490 --> 00:08:45.946
love posting things that
they should not post, and PR.

00:08:45.946 --> 00:08:47.570
And it was a lot less
marketing than it

00:08:47.570 --> 00:08:50.520
was some of the managing
kinds of things.

00:08:50.520 --> 00:08:53.552
And so the last
role I had at Wells

00:08:53.552 --> 00:08:55.010
was actually in
the community bank.

00:08:55.010 --> 00:08:56.930
And all of you know
where that is right now,

00:08:56.930 --> 00:08:59.840
so I'm happy to be at TIAA.

00:08:59.840 --> 00:09:03.680
So you know, I mean each of
those twists and turns involved

00:09:03.680 --> 00:09:05.690
some component of no
one wanted to touch it.

00:09:05.690 --> 00:09:07.250
Like my last role,
community banking,

00:09:07.250 --> 00:09:09.080
no one wanted to touch
that, because everyone

00:09:09.080 --> 00:09:10.310
knew there were
problems and things

00:09:10.310 --> 00:09:11.559
were getting ready to blow up.

00:09:11.559 --> 00:09:13.340
And that's what happened.

00:09:13.340 --> 00:09:15.170
So, yeah.

00:09:15.170 --> 00:09:16.010
Does that help?

00:09:16.010 --> 00:09:16.635
SPEAKER 1: Yes.

00:09:19.100 --> 00:09:22.612
Just taking a step
even further back,

00:09:22.612 --> 00:09:24.320
what was the first
job that you ever had,

00:09:24.320 --> 00:09:27.740
and did you imagine in that job
that you would find yourself

00:09:27.740 --> 00:09:29.325
here in this current role?

00:09:29.325 --> 00:09:30.780
RENEE BROWN: Mm-mm.

00:09:30.780 --> 00:09:35.180
I think all of you would say
the same thing, I would assume.

00:09:35.180 --> 00:09:37.700
I started my first
job at the age of 16

00:09:37.700 --> 00:09:39.260
on my birthday at 6:00 AM.

00:09:39.260 --> 00:09:40.490
I was a radio announcer.

00:09:40.490 --> 00:09:42.590
And the reason is my sister
was a radio announcer

00:09:42.590 --> 00:09:44.190
and we sound a lot alike.

00:09:44.190 --> 00:09:46.220
And so that's how
I got my first job,

00:09:46.220 --> 00:09:48.330
because I sound like my sister.

00:09:48.330 --> 00:09:51.310
But she continued in radio
for a lot longer than I did.

00:09:51.310 --> 00:09:53.040
But that was really great.

00:09:53.040 --> 00:09:53.850
I learned a lot.

00:09:53.850 --> 00:09:56.870
I did radio announcing
from that age into college.

00:09:56.870 --> 00:09:59.840
And I was actually a traffic
reporter in Baton Rouge

00:09:59.840 --> 00:10:01.007
where there's awful traffic.

00:10:01.007 --> 00:10:02.673
If you all have ever
been through there,

00:10:02.673 --> 00:10:05.420
you know, but I actually flew
in the airplane every morning,

00:10:05.420 --> 00:10:05.920
every night.

00:10:05.920 --> 00:10:10.090
And I was uptown Renee
Brown for a long time

00:10:10.090 --> 00:10:11.110
through graduate school.

00:10:11.110 --> 00:10:14.110
And every job I ever did--

00:10:14.110 --> 00:10:16.115
and during college,
I took any job

00:10:16.115 --> 00:10:17.740
I could working my
way through college.

00:10:17.740 --> 00:10:20.270
I was a receptionist for
an architectural firm.

00:10:20.270 --> 00:10:22.210
I worked at the library.

00:10:22.210 --> 00:10:25.210
You name it just to get money,
because, believe it or not,

00:10:25.210 --> 00:10:28.720
being a radio announcer
isn't very lucrative.

00:10:28.720 --> 00:10:32.110
But what I learned announcing
traffic in particular

00:10:32.110 --> 00:10:33.430
is you have 30 seconds.

00:10:33.430 --> 00:10:36.124
And you know, sometimes you'd
have two interstates shut down.

00:10:36.124 --> 00:10:38.290
You had all this stuff to
say and you had 30 seconds

00:10:38.290 --> 00:10:39.220
to get it done.

00:10:39.220 --> 00:10:41.440
And how did that translate
to my later jobs?

00:10:41.440 --> 00:10:43.270
I mean some of my
roles, and you have all

00:10:43.270 --> 00:10:46.330
experienced that, you go
in for a big presentation

00:10:46.330 --> 00:10:49.660
with somebody and they
want the 30 second version.

00:10:49.660 --> 00:10:51.650
And so to have that
experience of saying,

00:10:51.650 --> 00:10:52.930
OK, I have 30 seconds.

00:10:52.930 --> 00:10:55.449
What are the three things
I can say in 30 seconds?

00:10:55.449 --> 00:10:57.490
And believe it or not,
that has been very helpful

00:10:57.490 --> 00:10:58.310
for my career.

00:10:58.310 --> 00:11:01.690
So even though knowing
media and that side of media

00:11:01.690 --> 00:11:04.060
has been helpful for
my marketing career,

00:11:04.060 --> 00:11:07.060
that's the piece that probably
was the biggest learning for me

00:11:07.060 --> 00:11:09.272
as a younger person growing up.

00:11:09.272 --> 00:11:10.730
But I did also
learn a lot in radio

00:11:10.730 --> 00:11:13.630
of exactly what not to do
from an HR sexual harassment

00:11:13.630 --> 00:11:16.314
standpoint.

00:11:16.314 --> 00:11:17.230
Very different indeed.

00:11:20.470 --> 00:11:22.750
SPEAKER 1: And then
pivoting towards--

00:11:22.750 --> 00:11:26.620
again, you're an out
LGBTQ identifying woman.

00:11:26.620 --> 00:11:31.150
How do you feel like identifying
as an LGBTQ woman, or generally

00:11:31.150 --> 00:11:34.330
more broader as a woman,
has positively or negatively

00:11:34.330 --> 00:11:36.932
affected your career
and your growth?

00:11:36.932 --> 00:11:38.890
RENEE BROWN: You know,
I think one thing that's

00:11:38.890 --> 00:11:41.710
true across LGBT and
other diverse segments

00:11:41.710 --> 00:11:45.700
is I think people gain
more empathy growing up

00:11:45.700 --> 00:11:47.590
when you are the
subordinated group

00:11:47.590 --> 00:11:51.020
for the majority of your
upbringing or your lifetime.

00:11:51.020 --> 00:11:52.750
And so understanding
what it feels

00:11:52.750 --> 00:11:54.520
like to be not in
the dominant group

00:11:54.520 --> 00:11:56.950
and having empathy and
tracking, because I

00:11:56.950 --> 00:12:00.490
used to pay attention a lot to
people's emotions in the room.

00:12:00.490 --> 00:12:02.830
I think some of you
probably have experienced

00:12:02.830 --> 00:12:04.480
that too to kind of
sense when things

00:12:04.480 --> 00:12:07.740
are going in the wrong
direction and redirect them.

00:12:07.740 --> 00:12:10.510
And so I think that empathy
is critical for anybody

00:12:10.510 --> 00:12:13.150
who is a leader of people
to really understand

00:12:13.150 --> 00:12:16.840
how to read a situation and
use that level of empathy,

00:12:16.840 --> 00:12:21.280
and also knowing how to
be both aware when you're

00:12:21.280 --> 00:12:24.706
in the dominant group and how do
you help people that aren't is

00:12:24.706 --> 00:12:26.830
an awareness level that a
lot of people don't have.

00:12:26.830 --> 00:12:28.829
Because usually when
you're in a dominant group,

00:12:28.829 --> 00:12:31.270
and you have power and
authority and all that stuff,

00:12:31.270 --> 00:12:32.810
you're unaware of it.

00:12:32.810 --> 00:12:34.937
And the best place to
look at this is airport.

00:12:34.937 --> 00:12:36.520
We were kidding
around about airports.

00:12:36.520 --> 00:12:39.940
It's so fun when like
something happens

00:12:39.940 --> 00:12:42.100
and everyone gets
messed up with a flight.

00:12:42.100 --> 00:12:45.760
It's fun to watch the super
privileged people freak out

00:12:45.760 --> 00:12:49.000
and just lose their mind because
they're being inconvenienced.

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:51.580
And that's a sure
example of people

00:12:51.580 --> 00:12:54.224
who are very unaware that
they have all this privilege.

00:12:54.224 --> 00:12:56.140
And once they're put in
a position without it,

00:12:56.140 --> 00:12:59.090
they don't even know how to
deal with the world around them.

00:12:59.090 --> 00:13:02.430
And so I think, for me,
being an LGBT leader

00:13:02.430 --> 00:13:05.170
and a female leader,
I kind of try

00:13:05.170 --> 00:13:09.350
to carry all that background
of when I wasn't an executive,

00:13:09.350 --> 00:13:12.070
and I didn't have the
power or authority,

00:13:12.070 --> 00:13:14.620
and how do I use
that for good as I've

00:13:14.620 --> 00:13:16.890
moved through my career.

00:13:16.890 --> 00:13:18.660
SPEAKER 1: Great.

00:13:18.660 --> 00:13:21.750
Do you recall a moment in
your career or in your life

00:13:21.750 --> 00:13:24.600
when you realize that
being visibly out

00:13:24.600 --> 00:13:27.980
would actually be an asset to
you, either in your career,

00:13:27.980 --> 00:13:31.290
or in your work with
nonprofits on boards, et Cetera

00:13:31.290 --> 00:13:32.040
RENEE BROWN: Yeah.

00:13:32.040 --> 00:13:35.520
You know, I think probably
the moment when-- you know,

00:13:35.520 --> 00:13:38.730
for a long time I was executive
sponsor of LGBT groups

00:13:38.730 --> 00:13:40.646
at Wachovia and then at Wells.

00:13:40.646 --> 00:13:42.270
And when we transitioned
over to Wells,

00:13:42.270 --> 00:13:43.650
there was a lot of conversation.

00:13:43.650 --> 00:13:45.840
And no one really
wanted to go talk

00:13:45.840 --> 00:13:48.450
to the head of compensation
around the whole gross up.

00:13:48.450 --> 00:13:51.210
This was before domestic--
when we had domestic partner

00:13:51.210 --> 00:13:55.070
benefits and you needed to gross
up people's taxes on health

00:13:55.070 --> 00:13:57.220
care for their partners.

00:13:57.220 --> 00:13:59.970
And that was the moment where
I realized I had access,

00:13:59.970 --> 00:14:02.940
I knew the head of HR, I knew
this guy in compensation,

00:14:02.940 --> 00:14:06.480
and the people in the ERG
didn't have that access.

00:14:06.480 --> 00:14:09.630
And it's like, OK,
this is a win-win,

00:14:09.630 --> 00:14:11.822
because I can go knock on
a door, and open a door,

00:14:11.822 --> 00:14:13.530
and have a conversation
that's different,

00:14:13.530 --> 00:14:16.150
because we're working with one
another on different things,

00:14:16.150 --> 00:14:17.920
not just this.

00:14:17.920 --> 00:14:19.920
And so that's a real asset.

00:14:19.920 --> 00:14:21.840
And what I have found
through the years

00:14:21.840 --> 00:14:24.210
is a lot of times there
are LGBT folks who

00:14:24.210 --> 00:14:25.810
are not out at higher levels.

00:14:25.810 --> 00:14:28.570
And that's a real shame, because
they're missing an opportunity.

00:14:28.570 --> 00:14:30.390
And you know, other
diverse groups

00:14:30.390 --> 00:14:32.154
aren't as supportive
one to another.

00:14:32.154 --> 00:14:33.570
And that's a shame,
because that's

00:14:33.570 --> 00:14:36.360
where we can really have a
voice and be able to have

00:14:36.360 --> 00:14:37.720
conversations differently.

00:14:37.720 --> 00:14:40.350
So that's how I've
seen it as an asset is

00:14:40.350 --> 00:14:43.230
to open doors for others
who weren't able to do that.

00:14:45.650 --> 00:14:47.150
SPEAKER 1: Have you
ever experienced

00:14:47.150 --> 00:14:50.066
adversity, and kind
of the converse side,

00:14:50.066 --> 00:14:51.440
as a result of
being out at work?

00:14:51.440 --> 00:14:54.080
And would you be OK sharing
one of those stories with us?

00:14:54.080 --> 00:14:54.830
RENEE BROWN: Sure.

00:14:54.830 --> 00:14:56.300
And this is probably
less at work.

00:14:56.300 --> 00:15:01.070
It's probably more a side
effect of being so comfortable

00:15:01.070 --> 00:15:01.830
at the office.

00:15:01.830 --> 00:15:04.640
And so this situation happened.

00:15:04.640 --> 00:15:06.650
I don't know what
the year was, but I

00:15:06.650 --> 00:15:10.760
was getting in a taxi in St.
Louis heading to the airport.

00:15:10.760 --> 00:15:12.920
You know, the AG
Edwards, now Wells Fargo,

00:15:12.920 --> 00:15:15.140
Securities' headquarters
is in St. Louis.

00:15:15.140 --> 00:15:18.560
And so get in the taxi, you know
normal chit chat conversation

00:15:18.560 --> 00:15:20.087
with the driver,
and he said, OK, so

00:15:20.087 --> 00:15:21.170
what does your husband do?

00:15:21.170 --> 00:15:22.070
I said, I don't have a husband.

00:15:22.070 --> 00:15:22.850
I have a wife.

00:15:22.850 --> 00:15:24.970
And she stays home
with our child.

00:15:24.970 --> 00:15:28.956
And he left the interstate
and went someplace

00:15:28.956 --> 00:15:30.830
that I knew wasn't on
the way to the airport.

00:15:30.830 --> 00:15:34.184
So I realized, great, I
just totally got some guy.

00:15:34.184 --> 00:15:36.600
And he's going to go chop me
up in little bits and pieces.

00:15:36.600 --> 00:15:38.750
And so I immediately
got on the phone with HR

00:15:38.750 --> 00:15:41.440
and I was just chatting with my
HR partner, because I'm like,

00:15:41.440 --> 00:15:43.190
I'm going to be on the
phone with somebody

00:15:43.190 --> 00:15:44.990
while whatever happens happens.

00:15:44.990 --> 00:15:46.640
And he wound up
driving through a park

00:15:46.640 --> 00:15:47.931
and then getting back on track.

00:15:47.931 --> 00:15:49.220
But he was very--

00:15:49.220 --> 00:15:53.240
he did not appreciate the fact
that I was very out and honest

00:15:53.240 --> 00:15:55.520
about my personal situation.

00:15:55.520 --> 00:15:57.530
And so that was like
a lesson for me.

00:15:57.530 --> 00:15:59.660
Like within the walls
of your workplace,

00:15:59.660 --> 00:16:02.240
you can be very honest, and
sometimes in other places

00:16:02.240 --> 00:16:05.090
it's good to say,
you know, whatever,

00:16:05.090 --> 00:16:07.040
not answer the question.

00:16:07.040 --> 00:16:10.040
But yeah, that was one
big learning for me

00:16:10.040 --> 00:16:12.140
that got me a
little bit worried.

00:16:12.140 --> 00:16:13.640
SPEAKER 1: I can
definitely say I've

00:16:13.640 --> 00:16:17.810
had similar Uber experiences.

00:16:17.810 --> 00:16:22.370
How do you and your wife balance
your career and your family?

00:16:22.370 --> 00:16:25.310
RENEE BROWN: You know, I don't
know if there ever really

00:16:25.310 --> 00:16:26.450
is work/life balance.

00:16:26.450 --> 00:16:27.960
A lot of people
ask that question.

00:16:27.960 --> 00:16:30.147
And I think there's
times of throttling up

00:16:30.147 --> 00:16:31.730
where you're completely
out of balance

00:16:31.730 --> 00:16:34.220
and it's needed at whatever
time that is in your career.

00:16:34.220 --> 00:16:36.350
I mean, if you fundamentally
change jobs or change

00:16:36.350 --> 00:16:37.922
companies, it's not
like you're going

00:16:37.922 --> 00:16:39.630
to have a whole lot
of work life balance.

00:16:39.630 --> 00:16:41.629
And so I think it's
important just to name that.

00:16:41.629 --> 00:16:43.136
But you can't
always have the out

00:16:43.136 --> 00:16:45.190
of balance kind of situation.

00:16:45.190 --> 00:16:49.070
And it's not always throttling
up and spending 20 hours a day.

00:16:49.070 --> 00:16:53.150
And so we have routines,
like many others,

00:16:53.150 --> 00:16:55.310
you know whether it's the
Sunday evening dinners,

00:16:55.310 --> 00:16:58.850
or another work/life
balance thing is actually

00:16:58.850 --> 00:16:59.960
turning the phone off.

00:16:59.960 --> 00:17:02.820
I do stop in the evenings
and have some quiet time,

00:17:02.820 --> 00:17:05.210
particularly as my
daughter has gotten older.

00:17:05.210 --> 00:17:06.200
Now she's 15.

00:17:06.200 --> 00:17:07.160
She's taller than me.

00:17:07.160 --> 00:17:09.260
She's smarter than
me, literally.

00:17:09.260 --> 00:17:13.700
Her SAT score is way better than
mine was as a senior already.

00:17:13.700 --> 00:17:17.369
But it's harder to have
a teen talk to you.

00:17:17.369 --> 00:17:20.416
And so we have to really
make time and have quiet time

00:17:20.416 --> 00:17:22.040
as a family in the
evenings to actually

00:17:22.040 --> 00:17:24.079
have a conversation happen.

00:17:24.079 --> 00:17:26.302
And then the other piece
is we do take vacations.

00:17:26.302 --> 00:17:28.010
And so I was telling
them I'm heading out

00:17:28.010 --> 00:17:30.690
next Wednesday, which
is a little stressful,

00:17:30.690 --> 00:17:33.440
but we're going to go
on a two week vacation.

00:17:33.440 --> 00:17:35.840
It's critical to actually
get some downtime,

00:17:35.840 --> 00:17:39.680
because it's easy to let
both relationship and family

00:17:39.680 --> 00:17:42.110
kind of fall apart with
all the things pulling

00:17:42.110 --> 00:17:43.220
at you from your work.

00:17:43.220 --> 00:17:45.650
And so we try not
to have that happen.

00:17:45.650 --> 00:17:48.410
I don't know if we're
successful all the time though.

00:17:48.410 --> 00:17:50.110
SPEAKER 1: No one's perfect.

00:17:50.110 --> 00:17:51.650
RENEE BROWN: No.

00:17:51.650 --> 00:17:53.570
SPEAKER 1: And you had
mentioned your sister

00:17:53.570 --> 00:17:57.930
and also that you serve as
a deacon for your church.

00:17:57.930 --> 00:17:59.810
How does religion
come into your life,

00:17:59.810 --> 00:18:03.430
and especially since it can
oftentimes be perceived as,

00:18:03.430 --> 00:18:06.080
by members of the
LGBTQ community,

00:18:06.080 --> 00:18:10.250
as being at times at odds
with being LGBTQ identified

00:18:10.250 --> 00:18:11.960
and being open
about it, so I would

00:18:11.960 --> 00:18:15.740
love to hear how you address
that with your own identity

00:18:15.740 --> 00:18:16.970
and with your own faith.

00:18:16.970 --> 00:18:17.450
RENEE BROWN: Yeah.

00:18:17.450 --> 00:18:18.900
I thought that would
be an interesting area.

00:18:18.900 --> 00:18:21.060
And I don't know if that's
something all of you

00:18:21.060 --> 00:18:21.950
have seen at Google.

00:18:21.950 --> 00:18:24.560
But with other companies
and other ERGS,

00:18:24.560 --> 00:18:26.800
working with Out and
Equal, for example,

00:18:26.800 --> 00:18:30.390
it's interesting that, as
companies expand and get

00:18:30.390 --> 00:18:32.960
faith ERGs, that
people see that there'd

00:18:32.960 --> 00:18:35.660
be a conflict between a
faith employee resource

00:18:35.660 --> 00:18:39.340
group and an LGBT resource
group, or LGBT and military.

00:18:39.340 --> 00:18:41.512
It's all kinds of
interesting thoughts

00:18:41.512 --> 00:18:43.220
around different
diverse groups and where

00:18:43.220 --> 00:18:44.604
they might agree or disagree.

00:18:44.604 --> 00:18:46.520
And I have a very different
perspective on it,

00:18:46.520 --> 00:18:49.280
particularly in the
last year and a half

00:18:49.280 --> 00:18:53.120
as we've seen all diverse
groups attacked equally

00:18:53.120 --> 00:18:57.290
by the administration, by
parts of the media where,

00:18:57.290 --> 00:18:59.150
if you're a person
with disabilities,

00:18:59.150 --> 00:19:02.720
somebody is picking on you,
you're a person of color, LGBT,

00:19:02.720 --> 00:19:03.320
you name it.

00:19:03.320 --> 00:19:04.880
Everyone seems to
be under attack.

00:19:04.880 --> 00:19:08.330
And so as we think about all
these different diverse groups,

00:19:08.330 --> 00:19:10.730
I think we as a collective
need to figure out

00:19:10.730 --> 00:19:15.410
how to work together and really
help the cause of anybody who's

00:19:15.410 --> 00:19:15.920
diverse.

00:19:15.920 --> 00:19:17.212
And so I think that's critical.

00:19:17.212 --> 00:19:18.836
And I don't think
we've figured it out.

00:19:18.836 --> 00:19:21.530
I mean, if you think of all the
diverse groups in the country,

00:19:21.530 --> 00:19:23.210
if we all actually
got together, we

00:19:23.210 --> 00:19:26.120
would have a huge voice against
what's happening in our society

00:19:26.120 --> 00:19:26.840
right now.

00:19:26.840 --> 00:19:28.430
And folks aren't doing that.

00:19:28.430 --> 00:19:31.280
And I think it's an opportunity.

00:19:31.280 --> 00:19:33.440
And with religion
specifically, that's

00:19:33.440 --> 00:19:36.290
where I've had the most dialogue
across difference with folks,

00:19:36.290 --> 00:19:39.680
because I welcome people
having a conversation who

00:19:39.680 --> 00:19:42.080
might feel like their
religion says that they

00:19:42.080 --> 00:19:45.070
can't support LGBT folks.

00:19:45.070 --> 00:19:47.200
And so those have been
difficult conversations.

00:19:47.200 --> 00:19:51.460
But everyone has helped move
forward just a little bit.

00:19:51.460 --> 00:19:53.560
My upbringing-- I
spent three days a week

00:19:53.560 --> 00:19:57.670
in a church that really thought
LGBT folks were going to hell

00:19:57.670 --> 00:19:59.740
and said it frequently.

00:19:59.740 --> 00:20:04.160
So I was damaged by my early
childhood religious experience.

00:20:04.160 --> 00:20:06.880
And so it wasn't until
we started a family

00:20:06.880 --> 00:20:09.640
and my wife made
me go to church,

00:20:09.640 --> 00:20:11.950
and we shopped for a
church and found one.

00:20:11.950 --> 00:20:15.290
And it took years of
healing, honestly,

00:20:15.290 --> 00:20:18.070
to be in a church
that basically feels

00:20:18.070 --> 00:20:21.010
the same way Pope Francis
feels is that all of us

00:20:21.010 --> 00:20:23.580
are made in God's image
and loved equally.

00:20:23.580 --> 00:20:27.384
And it takes a long time to
heal from some of the scars

00:20:27.384 --> 00:20:29.050
if you've heard other
tapes in your head

00:20:29.050 --> 00:20:30.490
throughout your upbringing.

00:20:30.490 --> 00:20:33.010
And so I just wanted to name
that, and then my sister

00:20:33.010 --> 00:20:37.070
being a minister, and a
reverend, and leading a church.

00:20:37.070 --> 00:20:39.310
I think it's an
important thing to name,

00:20:39.310 --> 00:20:41.170
because I know
other LGBT folks who

00:20:41.170 --> 00:20:44.380
left any semblance of
faith out of their lives

00:20:44.380 --> 00:20:46.510
for any number of reasons.

00:20:46.510 --> 00:20:49.100
You know, pride parades, people
holler and screaming at you,

00:20:49.100 --> 00:20:49.880
things like that.

00:20:49.880 --> 00:20:51.340
It can be very disconcerting.

00:20:51.340 --> 00:20:53.200
But you know,
times have changed.

00:20:53.200 --> 00:20:54.850
And I think it's
time for us to have

00:20:54.850 --> 00:20:56.770
good dialogue and a
real understanding

00:20:56.770 --> 00:20:59.710
of different areas
of faith, and open up

00:20:59.710 --> 00:21:05.110
dialogue between an LGBTQ
ERG, and a faith ERG,

00:21:05.110 --> 00:21:09.700
and be visible in that, because
to say I'm a lesbian Christian,

00:21:09.700 --> 00:21:12.020
I'm very comfortable
saying that now.

00:21:12.020 --> 00:21:12.520
Now.

00:21:12.520 --> 00:21:14.946
Years ago I wasn't for
a number of reasons.

00:21:14.946 --> 00:21:16.820
But I just think that's
an important dialogue

00:21:16.820 --> 00:21:20.061
that a lot of companies aren't
having that conversation.

00:21:20.061 --> 00:21:22.560
SPEAKER 1: It sounds like also,
based on your earlier coming

00:21:22.560 --> 00:21:25.260
out story, that it's something
your sister also deals

00:21:25.260 --> 00:21:26.440
with in her faith as well.

00:21:26.440 --> 00:21:27.190
RENEE BROWN: Yeah.

00:21:27.190 --> 00:21:27.690
Yeah.

00:21:30.416 --> 00:21:32.040
SPEAKER 1: And you
also touched on this

00:21:32.040 --> 00:21:35.540
in terms of working together
as different minority groups.

