I realized, OK, I

00:33:06.639 --> 00:33:09.180
can create a common ground with
people who probably had never

00:33:09.180 --> 00:33:13.080
talked to a lesbian
leader before, honestly,

00:33:13.080 --> 00:33:14.850
or saw them in any
way where there

00:33:14.850 --> 00:33:16.440
was some kind of common ground.

00:33:16.440 --> 00:33:20.340
And that's where it cemented for
me that I need to be a leader

00:33:20.340 --> 00:33:22.270
and show up in the right ways.

00:33:22.270 --> 00:33:25.470
And then also, as you start
getting older in your career,

00:33:25.470 --> 00:33:28.110
you realize people younger than
you are actually watching you.

00:33:28.110 --> 00:33:31.500
And so I feel responsibility
around that, where it's like,

00:33:31.500 --> 00:33:36.000
I need to handle myself
in a way that is something

00:33:36.000 --> 00:33:38.980
people would want to follow.

00:33:38.980 --> 00:33:39.480
Thank you.

00:33:42.595 --> 00:33:43.970
AUDIENCE: Thank
you again so much

00:33:43.970 --> 00:33:46.370
for coming and talking today.

00:33:46.370 --> 00:33:47.840
My question for
you is how do you

00:33:47.840 --> 00:33:52.940
think that the folks
running the LGBT ERGs

00:33:52.940 --> 00:33:55.730
can best engage with more
senior folks, especially given

00:33:55.730 --> 00:33:58.520
that time is frequently
difficult to come

00:33:58.520 --> 00:34:00.950
by as folks get more and
more senior in their career?

00:34:00.950 --> 00:34:01.700
RENEE BROWN: Yeah.

00:34:01.700 --> 00:34:03.120
That's a great question.

00:34:03.120 --> 00:34:05.690
And one of the things
that really surprised me

00:34:05.690 --> 00:34:11.880
when I joined TIAA last year,
we had a panel, LGBT panel.

00:34:11.880 --> 00:34:14.969
And I think it was
on Coming Out Day.

00:34:14.969 --> 00:34:17.090
It was October 11 last year.

00:34:17.090 --> 00:34:20.690
And what really surprised
me is as the panel started,

00:34:20.690 --> 00:34:22.730
in walked the entire
executive committee,

00:34:22.730 --> 00:34:25.190
our CEO and all of his
direct reports except

00:34:25.190 --> 00:34:27.090
for maybe two who
couldn't make it.

00:34:27.090 --> 00:34:29.570
And that was the first
time in any of the time

00:34:29.570 --> 00:34:31.312
I've done this,
in the two decades

00:34:31.312 --> 00:34:33.020
I've been playing
around with this stuff,

00:34:33.020 --> 00:34:36.590
that the entire executive
committee joined an LGBT event.

00:34:36.590 --> 00:34:37.780
And that just floored me.

00:34:37.780 --> 00:34:39.070
And it was really impactful.

00:34:39.070 --> 00:34:42.409
It made me realize
TIAA really walks

00:34:42.409 --> 00:34:46.190
the talk around the
importance of all of the ERGs

00:34:46.190 --> 00:34:49.860
because they would do that with
other employee resource groups.

00:34:49.860 --> 00:34:52.940
And so I don't think that
is unusual for the company,

00:34:52.940 --> 00:34:55.280
but I think that's something
where you guys should

00:34:55.280 --> 00:34:57.530
ask leadership to
actually join and be

00:34:57.530 --> 00:35:02.980
visible in different events
because that goes a long way.

00:35:02.980 --> 00:35:05.930
Certain folks might show up
for some events and not others.

00:35:05.930 --> 00:35:08.740
It tells a story about
who's not present.

00:35:08.740 --> 00:35:10.490
So that would be one
thing, is making sure

00:35:10.490 --> 00:35:14.120
that the leadership is present,
but finding the right network.

00:35:14.120 --> 00:35:15.560
So I'm sure within--

00:35:15.560 --> 00:35:17.910
how many employees do
you guys have at Google?

00:35:17.910 --> 00:35:19.015
AUDIENCE: 80,000 or
something like that.

00:35:19.015 --> 00:35:19.410
RENEE BROWN: Oh, really?

00:35:19.410 --> 00:35:21.350
OK, I thought it was
a little bit bigger.

00:35:21.350 --> 00:35:24.920
If you think about the
entire organization, have you

00:35:24.920 --> 00:35:28.310
guys mapped out where
the rising leaders are,

00:35:28.310 --> 00:35:30.290
and really making sure
that they have a voice

00:35:30.290 --> 00:35:34.190
and are using their voice
both for LGBT and otherwise.

00:35:34.190 --> 00:35:35.120
That's important.

00:35:35.120 --> 00:35:36.390
And with talent review--

00:35:36.390 --> 00:35:38.390
I'm sure your company
does talent reviews, where

00:35:38.390 --> 00:35:41.180
people go through and say
who's the upcoming talent.

00:35:41.180 --> 00:35:44.540
And they always flag whether
they are in a diverse group.

00:35:44.540 --> 00:35:47.000
You've got to advocate to
have a rainbow on there.

00:35:47.000 --> 00:35:48.740
And so I'm doing that
now at our company.

00:35:48.740 --> 00:35:50.156
It's complicated
because there are

00:35:50.156 --> 00:35:52.550
some legal issues around
it, but if you just

00:35:52.550 --> 00:35:54.500
are showing if
somebody is a female

00:35:54.500 --> 00:35:56.870
and whether they're a person
of color, that's great,

00:35:56.870 --> 00:35:59.030
but we also need to have
the LGBT thing there.

00:35:59.030 --> 00:36:01.363
Because that's one of the
reasons people don't come out.

00:36:01.363 --> 00:36:02.780
They don't see it
as an advantage

00:36:02.780 --> 00:36:04.560
as they're moving
up in their career.

00:36:04.560 --> 00:36:07.850
So advocating as an ERG
to have talent reviews

00:36:07.850 --> 00:36:11.360
include people who are
openly willing to share that.

00:36:11.360 --> 00:36:14.840
Because to me, I
hired a friend of mine

00:36:14.840 --> 00:36:16.460
who's an
African-American gay man.

00:36:16.460 --> 00:36:17.830
I'm like, that's a twofer.

00:36:17.830 --> 00:36:21.190
We need to get double
bonus points for that.

00:36:21.190 --> 00:36:23.360
And so anyway, advocating
for that at the company

00:36:23.360 --> 00:36:25.850
is important because
every diverse group

00:36:25.850 --> 00:36:28.970
that somebody has within
them, every additional one,

00:36:28.970 --> 00:36:31.850
is more experience around
things that all of us

00:36:31.850 --> 00:36:32.722
need to learn from.

00:36:32.722 --> 00:36:34.430
So those are some of
the thoughts I have.

00:36:34.430 --> 00:36:36.596
But engaging your senior
leadership to attend events

00:36:36.596 --> 00:36:41.504
is a very outward display of
support that I would recommend.

00:36:41.504 --> 00:36:43.670
AUDIENCE: In the vein of
this question that you just

00:36:43.670 --> 00:36:50.570
answered, how do you think that
your own rise over the years

00:36:50.570 --> 00:36:55.370
have affected your ability to
do what you just said, advocate

00:36:55.370 --> 00:36:58.480
and whatnot?

00:36:58.480 --> 00:37:02.140
RENEE BROWN: I find that I've
been very lucky in my career

00:37:02.140 --> 00:37:03.107
as I've moved up.

00:37:03.107 --> 00:37:05.440
But honestly, I think a lot
of it is a lot of hard work,

00:37:05.440 --> 00:37:08.500
just like all of you have
experienced, that you have

00:37:08.500 --> 00:37:10.150
to do a ton of
hard work and a ton

00:37:10.150 --> 00:37:14.170
of caring for people, and
then doors are open for you.

00:37:14.170 --> 00:37:16.900
But having a voice on
LGBT, I'll tell you,

00:37:16.900 --> 00:37:19.270
I've had many situations
where I've come really

00:37:19.270 --> 00:37:20.920
close to not saying anything.

00:37:20.920 --> 00:37:23.260
Being the person in the
room saying excuse me,

00:37:23.260 --> 00:37:25.990
you just use language that
really isn't appropriate

00:37:25.990 --> 00:37:28.930
and can be offensive to people.

00:37:28.930 --> 00:37:29.710
That's important.

00:37:29.710 --> 00:37:31.620
But one thing I
would tell you is,

00:37:31.620 --> 00:37:33.520
it was about midway
through my career

00:37:33.520 --> 00:37:37.240
that I realized I have less
a voice on LGBTQ matters

00:37:37.240 --> 00:37:40.630
than I do watching out
for my people of color

00:37:40.630 --> 00:37:42.350
because I'm not a
person of color.

00:37:42.350 --> 00:37:44.980
I have more of a voice
going after something

00:37:44.980 --> 00:37:47.710
if I see an issue around
that because I have nothing

00:37:47.710 --> 00:37:48.610
to gain in it.

00:37:48.610 --> 00:37:50.359
Whereas some people
will see, well, that's

00:37:50.359 --> 00:37:52.780
just the angry lesbian
or the angry gay man

00:37:52.780 --> 00:37:54.200
fussing about something.

00:37:54.200 --> 00:37:57.460
So that's why I point out,
how do we help other ERGs?

00:37:57.460 --> 00:38:00.170
How can we give voice to
people who don't have voices?

00:38:00.170 --> 00:38:01.940
And I think that's
where power comes in.

00:38:01.940 --> 00:38:06.210
So I try to go beyond being
an LGBT leader to being,

00:38:06.210 --> 00:38:07.870
I'm a leader trying
to help diversity

00:38:07.870 --> 00:38:10.570
at the company and inclusion,
which is super critical.

00:38:10.570 --> 00:38:12.610
Because when you get to
the point of inclusion,

00:38:12.610 --> 00:38:14.290
it goes to a lot of things
that a lot of companies

00:38:14.290 --> 00:38:15.160
don't talk about.

00:38:15.160 --> 00:38:16.510
It gets to how people look.

00:38:16.510 --> 00:38:19.270
It gets to their social
class and social status.

00:38:19.270 --> 00:38:20.890
It gets to weight.

00:38:20.890 --> 00:38:23.050
It gets to-- let's
start naming things

00:38:23.050 --> 00:38:25.810
that cause people to
be in the out group.

00:38:25.810 --> 00:38:27.520
That area of
inclusion is something

00:38:27.520 --> 00:38:32.110
that all of us who understand or
have ever been on the receiving

00:38:32.110 --> 00:38:34.480
end of being excluded
for something,

00:38:34.480 --> 00:38:36.550
we all have to be a voice
to make sure everyone

00:38:36.550 --> 00:38:37.520
is included in things.

00:38:37.520 --> 00:38:39.610
Because that's how
companies do a better job,

00:38:39.610 --> 00:38:40.795
teams do a better job.

00:38:40.795 --> 00:38:43.730
So I'd say yes, I've
had a voice with LGBT.

00:38:43.730 --> 00:38:46.810
But I've seen more power helping
other groups that I'm not

00:38:46.810 --> 00:38:49.840
a member of every day.

00:38:49.840 --> 00:38:52.360
AUDIENCE: But you
have, over the years,

00:38:52.360 --> 00:38:55.080
more recently, do
you feel like you

00:38:55.080 --> 00:38:58.810
were more or less able to
do that because of the roles

00:38:58.810 --> 00:39:00.402
that you take now?

00:39:00.402 --> 00:39:01.360
RENEE BROWN: More able.

00:39:01.360 --> 00:39:01.860
Yeah.

00:39:01.860 --> 00:39:04.930
I mean, the more resources you
have, the more budget you have,

00:39:04.930 --> 00:39:05.770
it's really great.

00:39:05.770 --> 00:39:07.186
Like so yeah, I
can write a check.

00:39:07.186 --> 00:39:09.454
AUDIENCE: But time
is not an issue?

00:39:09.454 --> 00:39:10.870
RENEE BROWN: Well,
I mean, we make

00:39:10.870 --> 00:39:12.710
time for whatever
is important, right?

00:39:12.710 --> 00:39:14.040
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:39:14.040 --> 00:39:15.430
OK, good.

00:39:15.430 --> 00:39:16.592
RENEE BROWN: Yeah.

00:39:16.592 --> 00:39:18.496
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:39:18.496 --> 00:39:19.924
RENEE BROWN: [LAUGHS]

00:39:20.880 --> 00:39:24.250
No, I mean, time
management, it's funny.

00:39:24.250 --> 00:39:27.470
We can get as much
done as we prioritize.

00:39:27.470 --> 00:39:28.620
Yeah.

00:39:28.620 --> 00:39:30.020
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:39:30.020 --> 00:39:33.770
So I guess there's something
to be said for if somebody

00:39:33.770 --> 00:39:37.920
is in one of the
companies that you

00:39:37.920 --> 00:39:44.190
work at that's in an ERG at
Google or TIAA or wherever.

00:39:44.190 --> 00:39:49.990
Then it's almost that
person is, I guess, already

00:39:49.990 --> 00:39:54.340
in a position of more
privilege than someone else

00:39:54.340 --> 00:39:56.960
because they do have
a seat at the table.

00:39:56.960 --> 00:39:58.780
So how do you advocate
for those people,

00:39:58.780 --> 00:40:02.860
whether they're in the queer
community or people of color

00:40:02.860 --> 00:40:05.980
or really any of these
intersectional groups

00:40:05.980 --> 00:40:09.460
who don't have that
seat at the table?

00:40:09.460 --> 00:40:12.220
When we look out at
our ERGs, they're

00:40:12.220 --> 00:40:16.750
not there because for various
reasons in our society,

00:40:16.750 --> 00:40:19.120
they haven't been
afforded that opportunity

00:40:19.120 --> 00:40:25.330
to even be here, not having the
access to the social capital,

00:40:25.330 --> 00:40:29.770
the educational capital, to
even get somewhere like here,

00:40:29.770 --> 00:40:30.790
to have that voice.

00:40:30.790 --> 00:40:33.180
How do you advocate for those
people that are basically

00:40:33.180 --> 00:40:34.179
outside of the system?

00:40:34.179 --> 00:40:35.720
RENEE BROWN: That's
a great question.

00:40:35.720 --> 00:40:37.636
I don't know if I have
an answer for that one.

00:40:37.636 --> 00:40:38.490
I would love to.

00:40:38.490 --> 00:40:40.830
Can you help me figure it out?

00:40:40.830 --> 00:40:42.539
AUDIENCE: I'll try.

00:40:42.539 --> 00:40:43.830
RENEE BROWN: That'd be awesome.

00:40:43.830 --> 00:40:44.330
Yeah.

00:40:44.330 --> 00:40:46.350
But no, I agree with you.

00:40:46.350 --> 00:40:49.170
As our society has spread
from the haves and have nots,

00:40:49.170 --> 00:40:51.630
it's even more of
an issue, where

00:40:51.630 --> 00:40:54.780
being able to figure out how
to get people out of situations

00:40:54.780 --> 00:40:58.800
where they feel completely
without any power to change

00:40:58.800 --> 00:41:02.020
anything is very hard.

00:41:02.020 --> 00:41:03.660
So thank you for the
question, but I--

00:41:03.660 --> 00:41:04.850
yeah.

00:41:04.850 --> 00:41:06.010
I don't have an answer.

00:41:06.010 --> 00:41:08.740
AUDIENCE: Appreciate the honest
answer because I don't know

00:41:08.740 --> 00:41:10.907
if anyone does have the answer.

00:41:10.907 --> 00:41:12.240
I guess we have to work on that.

00:41:12.240 --> 00:41:13.040
RENEE BROWN: Yeah.

00:41:13.040 --> 00:41:15.623
That's what we're thinking the
next generation is going to do.

00:41:17.945 --> 00:41:19.820
Because the next generation
is always smarter

00:41:19.820 --> 00:41:20.569
than the last one.

00:41:20.569 --> 00:41:21.120
Yes, sir?

00:41:21.120 --> 00:41:23.090
AUDIENCE: I have
one more question.

00:41:23.090 --> 00:41:25.430
So I feel like just
hearing you speak,

00:41:25.430 --> 00:41:28.850
you have this amazing
confidence about your identity

00:41:28.850 --> 00:41:30.920
and sort of your role.

00:41:30.920 --> 00:41:33.830
And you talked about
sort of what made

00:41:33.830 --> 00:41:35.900
you come out in the workplace.

00:41:35.900 --> 00:41:40.430
But I guess my question
is more, have you

00:41:40.430 --> 00:41:44.700
always had that confidence or
has it developed over time,

00:41:44.700 --> 00:41:48.440
especially, I guess, along
with how general perceptions

00:41:48.440 --> 00:41:52.610
of LGBTQ people have changed?

00:41:52.610 --> 00:41:53.360
RENEE BROWN: Yeah.

00:41:53.360 --> 00:41:54.318
That's a good question.

00:41:54.318 --> 00:41:57.470
I mean, I think I've always
enjoyed being a leader

00:41:57.470 --> 00:42:01.400
and have had some level
of confidence, but not

00:42:01.400 --> 00:42:04.940
with myself, personally.

00:42:04.940 --> 00:42:08.120
I was probably 26
before I really

00:42:08.120 --> 00:42:09.570
was comfortable with myself.

00:42:09.570 --> 00:42:12.080
And I think that whole
process of coming out

00:42:12.080 --> 00:42:15.230
and talking to people and
being honest with people.

00:42:15.230 --> 00:42:18.560
Because for so long, I wasn't
fully honest with people.

00:42:18.560 --> 00:42:22.349
And yeah, just a funny
story, when I was pregnant

00:42:22.349 --> 00:42:23.390
and I'd walk into rooms--

00:42:23.390 --> 00:42:25.670
I had this job where I had to
meet with all kinds of people.

00:42:25.670 --> 00:42:26.780
And when you're
obviously pregnant,

00:42:26.780 --> 00:42:28.487
it's the same
question every time.

00:42:28.487 --> 00:42:30.070
It's like, oh, Renee,
you're pregnant.

00:42:30.070 --> 00:42:30.829
Congratulations.

00:42:30.829 --> 00:42:32.120
I didn't know you were married.

00:42:32.120 --> 00:42:33.950
And I'd say, well,
I'm not married.

00:42:33.950 --> 00:42:36.437
And they would be like,
OK, what do I say now?

00:42:36.437 --> 00:42:38.020
They were like, oh,
she's just a slut.

00:42:38.020 --> 00:42:39.343
[LAUGHTER]

00:42:39.343 --> 00:42:40.670
No.

00:42:40.670 --> 00:42:43.790
And then I would just start
talking and helping them

00:42:43.790 --> 00:42:45.502
understand the whole story.

00:42:45.502 --> 00:42:47.960
But I had to do that over and
over and over and over again.

00:42:47.960 --> 00:42:49.720
And if I didn't
have to do that, I

00:42:49.720 --> 00:42:51.636
don't think I would have
gotten as comfortable

00:42:51.636 --> 00:42:55.710
as quickly because it was
awkward and all of that stuff.

00:42:55.710 --> 00:42:58.490
And then it gave me a platform.

00:42:58.490 --> 00:43:02.297
And so anyway, it
was almost like not

00:43:02.297 --> 00:43:04.130
being a straight person
is not a good thing.

00:43:04.130 --> 00:43:05.921
It's not something
you'd put on your resume

00:43:05.921 --> 00:43:07.380
or that your parents
are proud of.

00:43:07.380 --> 00:43:10.800
And so it takes a lot of
years before you're like,

00:43:10.800 --> 00:43:11.510
OK, this is me.

00:43:11.510 --> 00:43:12.740
It's who I am.

00:43:12.740 --> 00:43:15.440
I'm doing cool stuff.

00:43:15.440 --> 00:43:16.560
And I'm good with myself.

00:43:16.560 --> 00:43:19.230
So I think it takes actually
being comfortable with yourself

00:43:19.230 --> 00:43:21.620
and getting through all that.

00:43:21.620 --> 00:43:24.442
And some people never are.

00:43:24.442 --> 00:43:26.700
Or people around them don't
let them be comfortable

00:43:26.700 --> 00:43:28.610
with themselves.

00:43:28.610 --> 00:43:31.740
But thank you for the question.

