so much confusion around,

00:44:17.380 --> 00:44:19.540
well, what does that
mean if somebody says,

00:44:19.540 --> 00:44:23.387
I'd like to be referred
to as they for somebody

00:44:23.387 --> 00:44:24.220
who's a baby boomer.

00:44:24.220 --> 00:44:25.760
And they're like, what in
the hell are you doing?

00:44:25.760 --> 00:44:27.850
What's going on with
the whole pronoun thing?

00:44:27.850 --> 00:44:29.980
And how do we
educate in a way that

00:44:29.980 --> 00:44:34.360
helps people not feel like this
is some sort of change that

00:44:34.360 --> 00:44:35.420
isn't needed.

00:44:35.420 --> 00:44:38.200
And so I think that dialogue
across a very different

00:44:38.200 --> 00:44:40.450
perspective is important
for the next generation.

00:44:40.450 --> 00:44:45.250
I mean, how do you explain a lot
of the continuums people are on

00:44:45.250 --> 00:44:47.890
related to gender and
explain it in a way that

00:44:47.890 --> 00:44:51.500
doesn't completely freak people
out to where they shut down?

00:44:51.500 --> 00:44:54.020
I think that's the biggest
challenge in this space

00:44:54.020 --> 00:44:56.290
because it is change to
some fundamental pieces

00:44:56.290 --> 00:44:59.230
that particularly the
boomer and older generations

00:44:59.230 --> 00:45:01.960
have held as capital T truth.

00:45:01.960 --> 00:45:04.450
And our next generation
is questioning

00:45:04.450 --> 00:45:07.140
all of that capital T truth.

00:45:07.140 --> 00:45:08.675
And I like that.

00:45:08.675 --> 00:45:09.550
I think it's awesome.

00:45:09.550 --> 00:45:12.655
So I would just try to
say, how do we educate

00:45:12.655 --> 00:45:13.780
in a way that's meaningful?

00:45:13.780 --> 00:45:16.660
And I actually have some friends
working on a concept that

00:45:16.660 --> 00:45:18.610
could really help with that.

00:45:18.610 --> 00:45:20.110
And it's called identiversity.

00:45:20.110 --> 00:45:22.720
And it helps understand
all the elements

00:45:22.720 --> 00:45:26.380
of gender, sexual
orientation, expression,

00:45:26.380 --> 00:45:29.440
because all of those things
can be confusing if you don't

00:45:29.440 --> 00:45:30.880
know how to think about them.

00:45:30.880 --> 00:45:33.220
And so I'm working with
them to get that out

00:45:33.220 --> 00:45:37.510
into different workplaces
to help explain and get

00:45:37.510 --> 00:45:42.850
into gender fluidity isn't
something to be scared of

00:45:42.850 --> 00:45:44.370
and all of that.

00:45:44.370 --> 00:45:47.580
But we need to figure out how
to educate, would be my answer.

00:45:47.580 --> 00:45:49.820
AUDIENCE: It's kind of tall.

00:45:49.820 --> 00:45:52.010
I'm wondering-- it's a
lot of responsibility,

00:45:52.010 --> 00:45:55.370
like you said, to educate
people to take moments and think

00:45:55.370 --> 00:45:57.320
about what's a
teachable moment, what's

00:45:57.320 --> 00:45:59.714
an appropriate moment
when you hold back.

00:45:59.714 --> 00:46:01.880
What's a question that you
wish people would ask you

00:46:01.880 --> 00:46:07.010
more often that would enable you
a platform that you could speak

00:46:07.010 --> 00:46:09.980
about something that people
are uncomfortable to ask you,

00:46:09.980 --> 00:46:13.760
either professionally
or related to LGBTQ?

00:46:13.760 --> 00:46:15.110
RENEE BROWN: Yeah.

00:46:15.110 --> 00:46:18.050
I think differences in
family is one of the ones

00:46:18.050 --> 00:46:19.550
that I find
interesting because we

00:46:19.550 --> 00:46:22.190
didn't know starting a family
what might be different.

00:46:22.190 --> 00:46:26.847
And come to find
out, it's really not.

00:46:26.847 --> 00:46:29.180
Because when you have a
teething baby-- somebody in here

00:46:29.180 --> 00:46:31.970
has a teething baby, I
remember talking-- yes.

00:46:31.970 --> 00:46:33.730
Doesn't matter if
you're straight, gay,

00:46:33.730 --> 00:46:36.290
anywhere on the continuum,
it's still a teething baby,

00:46:36.290 --> 00:46:39.050
and to be able to have people
that you can come together

00:46:39.050 --> 00:46:41.540
with and ask help for.

00:46:41.540 --> 00:46:44.480
So that whole
family piece is one.

00:46:44.480 --> 00:46:46.940
But I've had some people ask
some pretty crazy questions.

00:46:46.940 --> 00:46:50.930
And so there's always
interest in conception.

00:46:50.930 --> 00:46:54.710
It's like, you wouldn't
ask that of anybody else.

00:46:54.710 --> 00:46:59.875
So there's some extremes people
go to around different things.

00:46:59.875 --> 00:47:02.000
I don't know if there's
ever been a question people

00:47:02.000 --> 00:47:04.470
aren't asking enough about.

00:47:04.470 --> 00:47:05.930
But yeah.

00:47:05.930 --> 00:47:06.560
Yeah.

00:47:06.560 --> 00:47:09.170
But the whole family piece
is probably important.

00:47:09.170 --> 00:47:11.780
And definition of families
have changed so substantially

00:47:11.780 --> 00:47:15.890
in our society, where
having an LGBT family, that

00:47:15.890 --> 00:47:18.180
was our experience
in the childbirth.

00:47:18.180 --> 00:47:20.270
We thought people might
be weird at the hospital,

00:47:20.270 --> 00:47:23.240
and this was back in 2003.

00:47:23.240 --> 00:47:24.525
And it was quite the opposite.

00:47:24.525 --> 00:47:26.150
All the nurses were
like, we're just so

00:47:26.150 --> 00:47:28.564
happy more than
one parent is here.

00:47:28.564 --> 00:47:30.230
Because they have a
lot of people coming

00:47:30.230 --> 00:47:32.320
in who are single parents
going into a situation

00:47:32.320 --> 00:47:33.720
that's going to be really tough.

00:47:33.720 --> 00:47:35.136
And so they're
like, we don't care

00:47:35.136 --> 00:47:36.890
what the makeup of
the family is, as long

00:47:36.890 --> 00:47:39.587
as there's more people
to help the child, which

00:47:39.587 --> 00:47:40.420
I found fascinating.

00:47:40.420 --> 00:47:43.918
It was real interesting
learning for me there.

00:47:43.918 --> 00:47:44.418
Yeah.

00:47:47.340 --> 00:47:50.270
Yeah, and I'm also
raising a straight ally.

00:47:50.270 --> 00:47:52.280
So I hope I do a
good job with that.

